{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586754"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:38:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:38:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15094"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15094"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7782"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64505"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7782"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15094"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49937"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8132"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18995"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21273"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64505"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EKidney stones (renal calculi) are solid deposits that form within the urinary tract. They vary in composition, size, clinical presentation and sites where they might be found in the renal tract (Image 1, 2, 3).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common composition of kidney stones?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium oxalate","Cystine","Struvite","Uric acid","Xanthine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium oxalate stones\u003C/strong\u003E are the most common type of kidney stone, accounting for approximately 80% of all cases. They form when calcium combines with oxalate in the urine under conditions of supersaturation.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStruvite stones\u003C/strong\u003E (magnesium ammonium phosphate) comprise about 10-15% of kidney stones and are associated with urinary tract infections caused by urease-producing bacteria. \u003Cstrong\u003EUric acid stones\u003C/strong\u003E form in approximately 5-10% of cases, typically in conditions of low urinary pH. \u003Cstrong\u003ECystine stones\u003C/strong\u003E are rare and occur in patients with inherited disorders of amino acid transport. \u003Cstrong\u003EXanthine stones\u003C/strong\u003E are extremely rare and are typically associated with inherited disorders of purine metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcium-containing stones (calcium oxalate and calcium phosphate) account for approximately 80% of all kidney stones.","Risk factors for calcium stones include hypercalciuria, hyperoxaluria, and hypocitraturia."],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Fontenelle LF, Sarti TD. Kidney Stones: Treatment and Prevention. Am Fam Physician. 2019 Apr 15;99(8):490-496. PMID: 30990297","Peerapen P, Thongboonkerd V. Kidney Stone Prevention. Adv Nutr. 2023 May;14(3):555-569. doi: 10.1016/j.advnut.2023.03.002. Epub 2023 Mar 9. PMID: 36906146; PMCID: PMC10201681"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49937"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15094"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21224"},{"type":"m